						               													<description>'&amp;#227;&amp;#129;&amp;#138;&amp;#229;&amp;#133;&amp;#131;&amp;#230;&amp;#176;&amp;#151;&amp;#227;&amp;#129;&amp;#167;&amp;#227;&amp;#129;&amp;#153;&amp;#227;&amp;#129;&amp;#139;&amp;#239;&amp;#188;&amp;#159;&amp;#239;&amp;#189;&amp;#158;&amp;#231;&amp;#180;&amp;#171;&amp;#233;&amp;#153;&amp;#189;&amp;#232;&amp;#138;&amp;#177;&amp;#231;&amp;#165;&amp;#173;&amp;#227;&amp;#130;&amp;#138;&amp;#239;&amp;#189;&amp;#158; (Ogenkidesuka? ~Ajisai Matsuri~) (How are you? &amp;#239;&amp;#189;&amp;#158;Hydrangea Festival) is a 2 player postcard game from Japan. &amp;quot;&amp;#227;&amp;#129;&amp;#138;&amp;#229;&amp;#133;&amp;#131;&amp;#230;&amp;#176;&amp;#151;&amp;#227;&amp;#129;&amp;#167;&amp;#227;&amp;#129;&amp;#153;&amp;#227;&amp;#129;&amp;#139;&amp;#239;&amp;#188;&amp;#159;&amp;quot; How Are You? is the name of the series of postcards being introduced. Hydrangea Festival is the first game and was produced in memory of the designer's grandfather. It is sold with 3 postcards, so you can mail a copy of the game to somebody you miss.&amp;#10;&amp;#10;In the game, players are trying to have raindrops fall onto the petal of the Hydrangeas to change their colours. The raindrops are pink or blue (the player's colours), and the flowers are pink or blue or purple.&amp;#10;&amp;#10;The flowers change colour in sequence: pink, purple, blue. So a blue raindrop on a pink flower turns it purple, and another then turns it blue. A blue drop onto a blue flower locks the colour in place. The same works in reverse for pink drops.&amp;#10;&amp;#10;Players take turns placing flowers in the garden, and then raindrops in the clouds. As the drops fall, the flowers change colour until the clouds have passed. Players win by having more flowers in their colour at the end.&amp;#10;user summary&amp;#10;&amp;#10;</description>
